  <li id="comment-65032" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://ThePerfectDetails.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Donna</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2017/05/april-30/#comment-65032"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-06-15T18:18:35-04:00">Thursday, June 15, 2017 at 6:18 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Dear Molly,<br />
I first found your podcast and found myself laughing and enjoying it so much that I found your book &#8220;Delancy&#8221; at my local library and I just finished reading it. I didn&#8217;t expect it, but I cried at the end of the book. I also recently listened to the &#8220;Bolognese&#8221; podcast and maybe the convergence of the two caused me to channel some sort of emotion to make me cry. (BTW I hate to cry and don&#8217;t do it often). But I think the tears were of compassion and &#8220;sisterhood&#8221; , if that&#8217;s a thing? Needless to say,  really enjoyed the book and am excited to make the tomato and corn salad when we hit tomato season here in the Boston area. I&#8217;ve been enjoying your blog a lot too and I am not usually one to leave comments but I wanted to let you know how much I enjoy your writing and in our world of uncertainty and discord, I believe your writing IS necessary. We need to be able to laugh and recall nostalgic moments and you do that so beautifully in your writing. I&#8217;m going through a reinvention of my career and hope one of these days to visit Seattle and enjoy a pizza and a cocktail at Delancy and Essex! I look forward to reading &#8220;A Homemade Life&#8221; and working through all the podcasts. With much gratitude,<br />
Donna<br />
P.S. I already have a SquareSpace website (which is fabulous) and I&#8217;m about to buy a ThirdLove bra and I eat Talenti gelato often. And I promise to write a review on Spilled Milk soon too!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
